ice, and Eve Rawson — framing the act as relief for “all those that are suffering for their country, for liberty, or for righteousness sake.” Phillis was to be freed within six months; the others at the age of twenty-four. The document, preserved in Middletown’s town records, served as a kind of moral epitaph for a man whose marble monument bore only names and dates."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"His first wife died within a year","body":"Eliot Rawson married Sarah Russell, daughter of Rev. William Russell of Middletown, who died barely a year into the marriage and was laid in Riverside Cemetery, leaving an infant daughter named Sarah to carry her name. Seven years later he married Ann Cushing of Providence, with whom he had seven more children."}],"slug":"elliot-rawson-1724"},"X00452":{"id":"X00452","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"death":{"year":1776},"gender":"female","parents":{"father_id":"X00450","mother_id":"H00361"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X00450","date_year":1764,"date_month":7,"date_day":19,"children_ids":["HD1414","HD1415","HD1416","HD1417","HD1418","HD1419","HD1420"]}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Ann Elizabeth Cushing","first_name":"Ann","middle_name":"Elizabeth","maiden_name":"Cushing","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"ann-cushing"},"H00361":{"id":"H00361","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"de